{
  "texts": [
    "Ganesan et al. [100] found that incorporating up to 20% sugar bagasse ash SCBA into concrete led to additional calcium silicate hydrate (C-S-H) formation, which refined the pore structure and reduced porosity, resulting in a denser and more compact matrix.",
    "Similarly, Bahurudeen et al. [101] reported that SCBA improved the pore structure and decreased capillary porosity, which is crucial for limiting water ingress and aggressive ions, thus enhancing concrete durability.",
    "Cordeiro et al. [102] observed that SCBA's pozzolanic activity reduced pore size and volume, leading to a more homogeneous microstructure with fewer micro-cracks and better mechanical properties.",
    "This was attributed to the dense C-S-H gel formation that fills voids and strengthens the interfacial transition zone (ITZ) between the cement paste and aggregates.",
    "Murugesan et al. [106] confirmed that SCBA promotes dense C-S-H gel formation, reduces micro-cracks, and improves durability by creating a more integrated microstructure."
  ]
}